version_unique_justification: Open Liberty versions are based on YY.0.0.n where YY is the two digit year of release and n is the release within the year. Open Liberty releases every 4 weeks up to 12 releases a year.
version_tags_justification: Open Liberty creates tags for each release. The 22.0.0.3 release tag is here: https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/tree/gm-22.0.0.3
release_notes_justification:
Each build contains a CHANGES.TXT which is a list of GitHub issues and their summary that went into the build. The issues are expected to be human understandable. In addition for each release there is a web accessible web page that describes the content. These webpages for all releases are available here: https://openliberty.io/blog/?search=release&key=tag

Open Liberty zero migration architecture means that breaking changes are not intended: https://openliberty.io/docs/22.0.0.3/zero-migration-architecture.html
release_notes_vulns_justification: Security Vulnerabilities are listed on this page including the versions that are affected and when fixed: https://openliberty.io/docs/latest/security-vulnerabilities.html
test_policy_justification: All new function is required to be tested and those tests much be automated into the build. New features use a specific issue template that includes instructions on how to document the testing so one of the project test SMEs can review the test plan to assure that the quality is there: https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/blob/integration/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature.md#fat-documentation
tests_are_added_justification:
Feature Test Summary issues are used to document the testing process. Below are links to the issues for function delivered in 2022.

https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/issues/19563
https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/issues/19274
https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/issues/17035

https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/issues/19905
tests_documented_added_justification: Instructions for an issue tracking new function cover this requirement: https://github.com/OpenLiberty/open-liberty/blob/integration/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature.md#fat-documentation
warnings_justification: Compiler warnings are enabled in the build.
crypto_published_justification: Only use crypto provided by Java
crypto_call_justification: Only use crypto provided by Java
crypto_floss_justification: Only use crypto provided by Java which is FLOSS
crypto_keylength_justification: Keylength requirements are enforced by Java
crypto_password_storage_justification: Liberty has a mode (not recommended for production) which stores passwords for authentication. This uses PBKDF2.
